[The following concise background information on equine influenza is
derived from the review "Influenza" in "Disease Factsheets," Center
for Food Security and Public Health (CFSPH), Iowa State University,
available at
<http://www.cfsph.iastate.edu/Factsheets/pdfs/influenza.pdf>.
"Equine influenza viruses mainly infect horses and other Equidae. The
2 subtypes known to cause disease in horses are H7N7 (equine virus 1)
and H3N8 (equine virus 2). There is less antigenic drift in these
viruses than in human influenza A viruses. The H7N7 virus is
currently extinct or present at only very low levels in some parts of
the world. In 1989, a novel strain of equine influenza [A/eq/Jilin/89
(H3N8)] caused a serious epidemic, with high morbidity and mortality
rates, in Chinese horses. This virus appears to be an avian influenza
virus. A related virus caused influenza in a few hundred horses the
following year [1990] but there were no deaths. The avian-like virus
continued to circulate in horses in China for at least 5 years
without further fatalities.
One equine H3N8 virus recently jumped into dogs."
A map of New South Wales is available at
<http://www.supertravelnet.com/maps/?action=selmap&country=108_9002_5&language=1>
A map of Queensland is available at
<http://www.supertravelnet.com/maps/?action=selmap&country=108_9004_5&language=1>.
- Mod.AS]
